T1  - The Real Consequences of Market Segmentation
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhr143
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 7
SP  - 2041
EP  - 2069
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We study the real effects of market segmentation due to credit ratings by using a matched sample of firms just above and just below the investment-grade cutoff. These firms have similar observables, including average investment rates. However, flows into high-yield mutual funds have an economically significant effect on the issuance and investment of the speculative-grade firms relative to their matches, especially for firms likely to be financially constrained. The effect is associated with the discrete change in label from investment- to speculative-grade, not with changes in continuous measures of credit quality. We do not find similar effects at other rating boundaries.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhr143
ER  - 



